// ============================================================================
// METAMORPHOSES ON A LAMENT
// Movement I: Passacaglia — "The Weight of Descent"
// ============================================================================
//
// The passacaglia is among music's most obsessive forms: a bass line repeats
// endlessly while the upper voices spin variations above it. There's something
// almost Sisyphean about it — the bass keeps falling, keeps returning to begin
// its descent again, while the music above struggles, ornaments, rages, accepts.
//
// Our ground bass is the descending tetrachord: A-G-F-E (in the bass, A2-G2-F2-E2).
// This four-note figure has been called the "lament bass" since the 17th century.
// Each note gets a full measure in 3/2 time, giving us a four-bar ostinato.
//
// The movement presents 8 variations, moving from sparse to dense, 
// from resignation to fury, and finally to a kind of exhausted peace.
// ============================================================================

Title: "Metamorphoses on a Lament - I. Passacaglia"
Tempo: 56
Time: 3/2

// The Cello states the ground alone — naked, inevitable
Part: Cello Instrument: Cello {
    // === GROUND STATEMENT (Bars 1-4) ===
    // Just the bones. The tetrachord descending.
    | A2 w. p |
    | G2 w. |
    | F2 w. |
    | E2 w. |

    // === VARIATION I (Bars 5-8): The Viola enters ===
    // A simple counterpoint. Two voices acknowledging gravity.
    | A2 w. |
    | G2 w. |
    | F2 w. |
    | E2 w. |

    // === VARIATION II (Bars 9-12): First Violin joins ===
    // The texture thickens. The descent becomes communal.
    | A2 w. mp |
    | G2 w. |
    | F2 w. |
    | E2 w. |

    // === VARIATION III (Bars 13-16): All four voices ===
    // The ground begins to ornament itself.
    | A2 h A2 q G2 h. |
    | G2 h G2 q F2 h. |
    | F2 h F2 q E2 h. |
    | E2 w. |

    // === VARIATION IV (Bars 17-20): Agitation ===
    // The bass becomes restless, eighth notes, but still falling
    | A2 q A2 q G2 q A2 q G2 q F2 q mf |
    | G2 q F2 q E2 q F2 q E2 q D2 q |
    | F2 q E2 q D2 q E2 q D2 q C2 q |
    | E2 w. |

    // === VARIATION V (Bars 21-24): The Storm ===
    // Forte, driving, the descent becomes anguished
    | A2 q A2 q A2 q G2 q G2 q G2 q f |
    | G2 q G2 q G2 q F2 q F2 q F2 q |
    | F2 q F2 q F2 q E2 q E2 q E2 q |
    | E2 h. E2 h. ff |

    // === VARIATION VI (Bars 25-28): The Break ===
    // Suddenly quiet. The bass moves to longer values.
    | A2 w. pp |
    | G2 w. |
    | F2 w. |
    | E2 w. |

    // === VARIATION VII (Bars 29-32): Decorated Descent ===
    // Ornamental, almost baroque in its grief
    | A2 h B2 q A2 q G2 h p |
    | G2 h A2 q G2 q F2 h |
    | F2 h G2 q F2 q E2 h |
    | E2 w. |

    // === VARIATION VIII - CODA (Bars 33-40): Resolution ===
    // The ground slows, stretches. Acceptance.
    | A2 w. pp |
    | G2 w. |
    | F2 w. |
    | E2 w. |
    | A2 w. ppp |
    | G2 w. |
    | F2 w. |
    | E2 w. |
}

Part: Viola Instrument: Viola {
